### Code

```Rust
pub trait AsIterator {
    type Item<'a> where Self: 'a;
    type Iter<'a>: Iterator<Item=Self::Item<'a>> where Self: 'a;
    fn as_iter(&self) -> Self::Iter<'_>;
}
trait Trait {
    type AsIter<'a>: AsIterator<Item<'a> = &'a u32> where Self: 'a;
    fn fun(&self) -> Self::AsIter<'_>;
}
fn test<T: Trait>(t: T) {
    let a = t.fun();
    let iter = a.as_iter();
    for x in iter {}
}
```


### Current output

```Shell
error[E0597]: `a` does not live long enough
  --> src/lib.rs:12:16
   |
12 |     let iter = a.as_iter();
   |                ^^^^^^^^^^^ borrowed value does not live long enough
13 |     for x in iter {}
14 | }
   | -
   | |
   | `a` dropped here while still borrowed
   | borrow might be used here, when `a` is dropped and runs the destructor for type `<T as Trait>::AsIter<'_>`

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0597`.
```


### Desired output

Unsure. Should this pass borrow check actually?


### Rationale and extra context

Not sure what this error is trying to say? `a` doesn't live long enough, because it's still used after drop. But the use after drop is... the drop itself!?

